{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489371"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:14:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:14:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"643"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/643"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.68,0.07,0.16,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"643"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42800"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/643"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"643"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27764"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"176"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11149"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44260"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42800"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents with a four-month history of fatigue and dyspnoea. She reports weight loss of three kilograms over this time-frame. She also reports a persistent dull pain in several areas including central chest pain and back aches. She has 10 pack-year smoking history and does not drink any alcohol. There is no other relevant past medical or social history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she appears pale. Her blood pressure is 132/86mmHg, pulse rate 90/min and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory examination reveals poor air entry at both bases. There is tenderness along her ribs and across her sternum on palpation. Abdominal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer haematological test results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 78 g/L (125 \u2013 160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC 10.4x10\u003Csup\u003E9 \u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0 \u2013 11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 298x10\u003Csup\u003E9 \u003C/sup\u003E/L (150 \u2013 450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer other laboratory investigations are shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia","Multiple myeloma","Metastasised renal cell carcinoma","Metastasised squamous cell carcinoma of the lungs","Sarcoidosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a prominent anaemia, of which a bone marrow cause should be considered as her history and examination do not support an acute cause of anaemia, such as haemorrhage. This patient\u0027s presentation is suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple myeloma (MM)\u003C/strong\u003E, including hypercalcaemia, renal dysfunction, anaemia and bone pain which may be due to lytic bone lesions (this may be remembered using the mnemonic \u0027CRAB\u0027).\u00a0The diagnosis of myeloma is further suggested by the history of constitutional symptoms and hyperglobulinaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL)\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by abnormal lymphocytes in the blood and bone marrow. While it can cause anaemia, it does not typically associated with bone pain. Common presentations of CLL include lymphadenopathy, hepatomegaly and splenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastasised renal cell carcinoma (RCC) \u003C/strong\u003Eis an advanced stage of kidney cancer which has metastasised to other sites such as the lungs, bones or liver. It can present with constitutional symptoms. However, RCC typically presents with haematuria and palpable abdominal mass in the abdomen. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastasised squamous cell carcinoma of the lungs \u003C/strong\u003Eis an advanced stage of lung cancer that can metastasised to bones and liver, causing pain in the affected area. It also present with constitutional symptoms as well as dyspnoea. Although squamous cell carcinoma of the lungs can be associated with paraneoplastic elevation in PTHrP resulting hypercalcaemia, it does not typically present with anaemia and raised globulins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis \u003C/strong\u003Eis an inflammatory condition resulting in non-caseating granulomas in the lungs and extra-pulmonary manifestations resulting in a number of symptoms. Sarcoidosis can present with constitutional symptoms such as fatigue and weight loss. Pulmonary symptoms can include dyspnoea, cough and chest pain. Extrapulmonary manifestations includes lymphadenopathy polyarthritis, erythema nodosum. Sarcoidosis can mediate increase production of vitamin D resulting in hypercalcaemia. However, sarcoidosis does not result in anaemia, increase globulins or kidney failure as suggested in the stem. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Multiple myeloma (MM) can present with signs and symptoms including hypercalcaemia, renal dysfunction, anaemia and bone pain which may be due to lytic bone lesions."],"references":["Michels TC, Petersen KE. Multiple Myeloma: Diagnosis and Treatment.\u00a0Am Fam Physician. 2017;95(6):373-383. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28318212/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27764"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"643"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"942"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/942"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2fe256dc-0779-436e-b21f-41822c458da9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2fe256dc-0779-436e-b21f-41822c458da9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":581,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27764"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-19T15:07:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-21T09:22:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"643"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42800"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu